Part 1: Basic simulation and NHST

Lets start by convincing ourselves that t-tests have the appropriate false positive rate. Run 10,000 t-tests with standard, normally-distributed data from a made up 30-person, single-measurement experiment (the command for sampling from a normal distribution is rnorm). Whats the mean number of significant results?

First do this using a for loop.

count_signif <- 0
for (t in 1:10000) {
  d <- rnorm(30, mean = 0, sd = 1)
  result <- t.test(d, mu = 0)
  if (result$p.value <= .05) {
    count_signif <- count_signif + 1
  }
}

prop_signif <- count_signif/10000; prop_signif
## [1] 0.0517

Next, do this using the replicate function:

count <- 0
rep <- replicate(10000, t.test(rnorm(30, mean=0, sd=1))$p.value <= .05)
count_signif <- sum(rep==TRUE)
prop_signif <- count_signif / 10000; prop_signif
## [1] 0.0489

Ok, that was a bit boring. Lets try something moderately more interesting - lets implement a p-value sniffing simulation, in the style of Simons, Nelson, & Simonsohn (2011).

Consider this scenario: you have done an experiment, again with 30 participants (one observation each, just for simplicity). The question is whether their performance is above chance. You arent going to check the p-value every trial, but lets say you run 30 - then if the p-value is within the range p < .25 and p > .05, you optionally run 30 more and add those data, then test again. But if the original p value is < .05, you call it a day, and if the original is > .25, you also stop.

First, write a function that implements this sampling regime.

double.sample <- function(n) {
  d <- rnorm(n)
  result <- t.test(d)
  if (result$p.value < .05) {
    return('Significant')
  } else if (result$p.value > .25) {
    return('Not significant')
  } else {
    d2 <- rnorm(n)
    result <- t.test(c(d, d2))
    if (result$p.value < .05) {
      return('Significant')
    } else {
      return('Not significant')
    }
  }
}
double.sample(30)
## [1] "Not significant"

Now call this function 10k times and find out what happens.

double_samp_result <- replicate(10000, double.sample(30))
sig <- sum(double_samp_result == "Significant")
false_pos_rate = sig/10000; false_pos_rate
## [1] 0.0701

Is there an inflation of false positives? How bad is it?

Yes, the false positive rate is much higher instead of being just under .05, it is now nearly .07.

Now modify this code so that you can investigate this double the sample rule in a bit more depth. Lets see what happens when you double the sample ANY time p > .05 (not just when p < .25), or when you do it only if p < .5 or < .75. How do these choices affect the false positive rate?

HINT: Try to do this by making the function double.sample take the upper p value as an argument, so that you can pass this through dplyr.

HINT 2: You may need more samples. Find out by looking at how the results change from run to run.

double.sample <- function(n, upper_p) {
  d <- rnorm(n)
  result <- t.test(d)
  if (result$p.value < .05) {
    return('Significant')
  } else if (result$p.value > upper_p) {
    return('Not significant')
  } else {
    d2 <- rnorm(n)
    result <- t.test(c(d, d2))
    if (result$p.value < .05) {
      return('Significant')
    } else {
      return('Not significant')
    }
  }
}

double_samp_result_100 <- replicate(10000, double.sample(30, 1))
sig_100 <- sum(double_samp_result_100 == "Significant")
false_pos_rate_100 = sig_100/10000; false_pos_rate_100
## [1] 0.0842
double_samp_result_75 <- replicate(10000, double.sample(30, .75))
sig_75 <- sum(double_samp_result_75 == "Significant")
false_pos_rate_75 = sig_75/10000; false_pos_rate_75
## [1] 0.0802
double_samp_result_50 <- replicate(10000, double.sample(30, .5))
sig_50 <- sum(double_samp_result_50 == "Significant")
false_pos_rate_50 = sig_50/10000; false_pos_rate_50
## [1] 0.0732

What do you conclude on the basis of this simulation? How bad is this kind of data-dependent policy?

This data-dependent policy is dangerous. Even if your results appear to approach significance (ie you have a p < .25), p-sniffing greatly increases the false positive rate, almost as much as if your results were not approaching significance. The elevated rates when rerunning all nonsignificant results is not that much different from the false positive rate from rerunning the analysis when you have a p < .25.

Thought question: Take a moment to interpret the coefficients of the model. Q1 - What are the units? The units of the coefficients are arbitrary. Since dose is quantitative, the coefficient represents the difference in the predicted value of the DV for each one-unit difference, if delivery method remains constants. Since delivery method is categorical, the coefficient is interpreted as a one unit difference representing a switch from one level to another.

Q2 - How does the interaction relate to the plot? The plot shows that at lower doses, both OJ and VC have a strong positive relationship with tooth length, but at higher doses the relationship is stronger for VC, whereas the slope for OJ flattens out.

Q3 - Should there be an interaction in the model? What does it mean? How important is it? There should be an interaction in the model, as OJ and VC do not appear to affect tooth length identically with increasing doses of vitamin C. This means that when using OJ as your source for vitamin C, at some point increasing your dosage does not boost tooth growth, while using VC continues to have a beneficial impact of dosage on tooth growth. This could be due to limits on absorption of vitamin C from OJ. This interaction is important because if increased tooth growth is needed, VC might be a better option than OJ for doses greater than 2.

Now make predictions from the model you like the best. What should happen with doses of 0, 1.5, 2.5, and 10 under both supplements?

HINT: use the predict function

HINT 2: you will have to make a dataframe to do the prediction with, so use something like data.frame(dose=...).

dose_df <- data.frame(dose = rep(c(0, 1.5, 2.5, 10), 2), supp = c(rep("VC", 4), rep("OJ", 4)))
predicted = predict.lm(rs_interaction, dose_df)

Brief Confidence Interval Digression

Start out by setting up a function for a 95% CI using the normal approximation.

# sample statistic +/- margin of error (critical value * sd/se)
sem <- function(x) {sd(x) / sqrt(length(x))}

ci95.norm <- function(x) {
  me <- sem(x) * qnorm(.975)
  c(mean(x) - me, mean(x) + me)
}

But the number of participants in a group is likely to be < 30, so lets also compute this with a t distribution.

ci95.t <- function(x) {
  me <- sem(x) * qt(.975, length(x)-1)
  c(mean(x) - me, mean(x) + me)
}

On the other hand, maybe we should use bootstrap CIs because these are actually proportions, and the normal/t approximations dont know that they are 0/1 bounded.

library(boot)
library(bootstrap)

Take a look at ?boot and ?bootci. Note that the syntax for the boot library is terrible, so were going to use it to check some code that I use:

theta <- function(x,xdata,na.rm=T) {mean(xdata[x],na.rm=na.rm)}
ci.low <- function(x,na.rm=T) {
  mean(x,na.rm=na.rm) - 
    quantile(bootstrap(1:length(x),
                       10000,theta,x,na.rm=na.rm)$thetastar,.025,na.rm=na.rm)}
ci.high <- function(x,na.rm=T) {
  quantile(bootstrap(1:length(x),
                     10000,theta,x,na.rm=na.rm)$thetastar,.975,na.rm=na.rm) - 
    mean(x,na.rm=na.rm)}

grouped <- d %>% group_by(age.group, condition) %>%

ggplot(grouped, aes(x = condition, y = m, fill = age.group)) + geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") + geom_errorbar(limits, position=position_dodge(width=.9), width=0.25) + theme_bw()

What do you conclude about confidence interval computation?

For a fairly large n, using the normal approximation, t approximation, and bootstrapping yields similar confidence intervals.

OK, now do a basic GLM over the entire data frame, using age.group, condition, and their interaction to predict correctness. (If we were focusing on developmental issues, I would ask you to think about how to model age here, but lets treat it as three discrete groups for now).

NOTE: this model is not appropriate, because it assumes that each subjects observations are independent from one another. Its still fine to do the analysis, though: it can tell you a lot about the data and is easy and fast to fit, as long as you know that you cant trust the p-values!

Lets now use dplyr to get data frames for by-items (msi) and by-subjects (mss) analyses. msi should contain the mean ratings for every item and mss should contain the mean ratings for every subject.

msi <- d %>% 
  group_by(trial) %>%
  mutate(m = mean(correct))

mss <- d %>%
  group_by(subid) %>%
  mutate(m = mean(correct))

Now do standard linear models on each of these.

NOTE: These are not strictly correct either because of the normal approximation on percent correct (model doesnt know its 0 - 1 bounded and could give you standard error that goes above 1). Again, useful to do and see what happens.

On to linear mixed effect models. Create the maximal random effects model a la Barr et al. (2013). Does it converge? If not, what will you do to make it converge? (The internet can be your friend here).

HINT: try simplifying your model to a semi-maximal model. Bonus: try using a different fitting procedure on the maximal model.

HINT: make sure that you consider which random effects are appropriate. Consider which observations are within/between subjects. E.g. having a random coefficient for age by subject doesnt make sense, because each subject has only one age.

How do these coefficients compare with the independent coefficients linear model? What do you conclude?

Which random effects make the most difference? Find out using ranef. Plot the random effects for subject and item.

Make the minimal random effects model with just a subject intecept. How does this compare?

Get an estimate of the significance value for the coefficient on the age*condition interaction by using anova to compare between your semi-maximal model and the model without an intercept.
